# Explanation of variables

## Top-level metadata

### `$schema`
Points to the JSON Schema used for validation.

### `schema_version`
Version of the configuration format.

### `id`
Stable machine-facing identifier.

### `label`
Human-readable display name.

### `description`
Short explanation of the preset.

### `enabled`
Whether the preset is active.

### `modality`
Broad sensing class such as visible or infrared.

### `variant`
Subtype such as rgb, mono, lwir, or mwir.

## `frames`

### `sensor_frame`
Name of the sensorâs own frame.

### `parent_frame`
Frame relative to which the sensor is mounted.

### `handedness`
Whether coordinates are left- or right-handed.

### `optical_axis`
Which axis points along the viewing direction.

### `up_axis`
Which axis defines image up.

## `mount`

### `position_m`
Translation relative to the parent frame, in meters.

### `rotation_deg`
Rotation relative to the parent frame, in degrees.

## `timing`

### `sensor_tick_s`
How often sensor logic runs.

### `frame_rate_hz`
Nominal output frame rate.

### `exposure_time_ms`
Integration time per frame.

### `readout_mode`
Usually global shutter or rolling shutter.

### `readout_time_ms`
Readout duration, especially important for rolling shutter.

### `latency_ms`
Delay from acquisition to output.

### `timestamp_source`
Which clock is used for timestamps.

## `optics`

### `projection_model`
Projection family such as pinhole or fisheye.

### `resolution_px`
Image size as width and height.

### `intrinsics_px.fx`
Horizontal focal length in pixels.

### `intrinsics_px.fy`
Vertical focal length in pixels.

### `intrinsics_px.cx`
Principal point x-coordinate in pixels.

### `intrinsics_px.cy`
Principal point y-coordinate in pixels.

### `intrinsics_px.skew`
Skew term of the intrinsic matrix, usually zero.

### `distortion.model`
Distortion model identifier.

### `distortion.coeffs.k1`, `k2`, `k3`
Radial distortion coefficients.

### `distortion.coeffs.p1`, `p2`
Tangential distortion coefficients.

### `f_number`
Lens speed.

### `focus_distance_m`
Distance of best focus.

### `transmittance`
Fraction of incoming energy passed by the optics.

### `vignetting.enabled`
Whether optical corner falloff is simulated.

## `sensor`

### `pixel_pitch_um`
Physical detector pitch in micrometers.

### `cfa_pattern`
Bayer arrangement for visible sensors.

### `quantum_efficiency`
Fraction of incoming photons converted into charge.

### `full_well_capacity_e`
Maximum electrons before saturation.

### `spectral_response_ref`
Reference to spectral response data.

### `detector_type`
Detector family, especially useful for IR.

### `band_um`
Spectral band in micrometers.

### `netd_mK`
Noise Equivalent Temperature Difference.

### `radiometric_mode`
Whether thermal output is intended to preserve measurement meaning.

## `electronics`

### `analog_gain_db`
Analog amplification before digitization.

### `digital_gain`
Numerical scaling after digitization.

### `iso_like_gain`
ISO-style user-facing sensitivity proxy.

### `black_level_dn`
Digital pedestal in darkness.

### `adc_bits`
ADC precision in bits.

### `saturation_dn`
Maximum digital code before clipping.

### `read_noise_e`
Readout noise referred to electrons.

### `dark_current_e_s`
Thermally generated charge per second.

### `dsnu_dn`
Dark Signal Non-Uniformity.

### `prnu_rel`
Photo Response Non-Uniformity.

### `quantization.enabled`
Whether ADC quantization is simulated.

### `bad_pixels.enabled`
Whether defect pixels are simulated.

### `bad_pixels.density_ppm`
Defect density per million pixels.

## `postprocess`

This is an ordered list because order matters.

Each stage contains:

### `stage`
Name of the processing operation.

### `enabled`
Whether the stage is active.

### `domain`
Signal domain in which the stage operates.

### `params`
Stage-specific parameter block.

Common examples:
- demosaic
- white_balance
- color_correction
- denoise
- sharpen
- tonemap
- gamma_encode
- agc
- colormap

## `output`

### `pixel_format`
Internal or exported pixel format.

### `color_space`
Color space such as sRGB or linear.

### `transfer_function`
Encoding function such as linear or sRGB.

### `bit_depth`
Saved bit depth per channel.

### `container`
File or export format such as png or exr.

### `channels`
Semantic meaning of output channels.

### `save_raw`
Whether raw-like output is saved.

### `save_processed`
Whether processed output is saved.

### `include_metadata_sidecar`
Whether metadata is exported alongside the image.

## `calibration`

### `intrinsics_source`
Where intrinsics came from.

### `distortion_source`
Where distortion parameters came from.

### `oecf_ref`
Reference to response or conversion characterization data.

### `calibration_date`
Date of calibration or fitting.

### `radiometric_calibration_ref`
